{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568045"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19458"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19458"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.08,0.06,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12185"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with a firm, whitish nodule on the helix of his left ear that has slowly enlarged over several years (Image). He has a history of gout affecting his feet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances is most likely to be found within this lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monosodium urate crystals","Cholesterol crystals","Sebum","Haemosiderin","Pus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lesion described is a gouty tophus containing \u003Cstrong\u003Emonosodium urate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E. Tophi are characteristic of chronic gout and commonly form in cooler body regions including the external ear, particularly the helix. They represent crystalline deposits that form during prolonged hyperuricaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol crystals\u003C/strong\u003E form in xanthomas, which appear as yellowish plaques typically associated with hyperlipidaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESebum\u003C/strong\u003E is found in sebaceous cysts, which present as soft, mobile lumps commonly found on the face and trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemosiderin\u003C/strong\u003E is an iron-storage complex that causes brown skin discolouration but does not form nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPus\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory exudate associated with acute infection and would cause pain, redness and warmth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of tophi indicates chronic gout with sustained hyperuricaemia and suggests the need for long-term urate-lowering therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gouty tophi commonly form in the external ear (helix) due to deposition of monosodium urate crystals in cooler body regions.","Tophi represent a chronic manifestation of gout and indicate prolonged hyperuricaemia.","The helix of the ear is a characteristic location for tophi along with fingers, toes, and olecranon bursa."],"references":["Hainer BL, Matheson E, Wilkes RT. Diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of gout. Am Fam Physician. 2014;90(12):831-836."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19458"}},"stemMedia":{"da